Scrooge’s transformation is illustrated by the parallels between his attitude and the
weather. At rst, when Scrooge is miserly and isolated, the weather is “bleak” and “biting”.
The word “biting” reects the impatient way he speaks to others, and the alliterative ‘b’
puts emphasis on both words, which in turn highlights the intensity of Scrooge’s miserable
demeanour. This contrasts starkly with his newfound joy in Chapter Five, which is illustrated
by the “clear” and “bright” weather. The word “clear” reects how his world view is no longer
clouded by misery and loneliness, and “bright” implies that he is now optimistic for the future.
The association between poor weather and unhappiness, and vice versa, is common in literature,
so these parallels encourage the reader to recognise Scrooge’s transformation as a positive one.
As Scrooge’s transformation is presented alongside changes in the wider environment, Dickens
could be suggesting that people like Scrooge can change society if they adopt a positive attitude.
The circular structure of the novella illustrates the extent of Scrooge’s transformation,
as events are revisited to show how he has changed. In Chapter Five, Scrooge encounters
the charity collector that he previously argued with. Where Scrooge left their rst meeting
only with an “improved opinion of himself”, he now worries how the man would “look upon
him”. This suggests that he has become more concerned about the effect his behaviour has
on others. Similarly, Bob Cratchit is initially referred to as “the clerk”: this impersonal,
business-like term shows Scrooge’s detachment from him. However, in the nal scene,
Scrooge calls Bob his “friend”. This shows how Scrooge’s attitude towards Bob has changed,
as he is now open to knowing him on a personal level. By revisiting scenarios from the
beginning of the novella, Dickens invites the reader to compare how Scrooge has changed.
This highlights his transformation and shows the reader how Scrooge is integrating into society.
Dickens also suggests that Scrooge’s transformation can transform the lives of the poor.
The Ghost of Christmas Yet to Come shows Scrooge that Tiny Tim will die if Scrooge doesn’t
change. Scrooge becomes a good “master” to Bob Cratchit and “a second father” to Tiny Tim,
and, as a result, Tiny Tim doesn’t die. By describing Scrooge as a “father”, Dickens emphasises
the close relationship he forms with the Cratchits and highlights the major role he plays in
transforming their lives. Scrooge’s inuence reects wider issues in Victorian society,
where the poor were often ignored by those who had the power to help them. Dickens, who
was an advocate for helping the poor through projects such as the Ragged Schools, uses the
novella to show that the rich were fundamental in changing the lives of the poor for the better.
Dickens uses Scrooge’s transformation to suggest that even the most miserly of people
can change their ways. Dickens shows Scrooge’s transition from a miser into a charitable
person through the imagery, contrasting language and circular structure of the novella.
This makes his transformation all the more vivid, and allows the reader to experience the
transformative power of the Christmas spirit, which Dickens hoped would change the attitudes
of those who read the novella for the better.
